stretch and get water and whatnot, and then we'll continue.

04:00.320 --> 04:07.520
So the first part is going to be my efforts to break down some common categories and some

04:07.520 --> 04:10.600
terminology that I think is really limiting the field.

04:10.600 --> 04:15.480
And so for this reason, we're going to talk about stretching that into a kind of continuum

04:15.480 --> 04:19.600
of various types of agents, and I want to show you some examples.

04:19.600 --> 04:26.440
So this is, even though this is fairly, fairly a very old view, this is a famous painting

04:26.440 --> 04:30.200
of Adam naming the animals in the Garden of Eden.

04:30.200 --> 04:34.080
This is still actually quite prevalent in many, many relevant discussions.

04:34.080 --> 04:40.520
What you see here is that there's a very sharp binary distinction between Adam here and the

04:40.520 --> 04:42.040
rest of the animals.

04:42.040 --> 04:47.800
So it's very clear that there are different kinds of creatures, fundamentally different

04:47.800 --> 04:48.880
kinds.

04:48.880 --> 04:57.920
But what we know now, because of Darwin and because of Von Baer, is that actually this

04:57.920 --> 05:02.600
notion that there's some kind of a sharp binary category of being a human is actually

05:02.600 --> 05:09.040
a smooth continuum, both on an evolutionary time scale, where if you slide back in evolutionary

05:09.040 --> 05:15.760
time, you see a very gradual set of changes that go from that human all the way back to

05:15.760 --> 05:17.880
a microbe and below that.

05:17.880 --> 05:23.440
And of course, even on the life scale of the individual itself, you see we all start life

05:23.440 --> 05:29.720
as a single cell, and then slowly and gradually we become what is basically considered to

05:29.720 --> 05:31.640
be a standard human.

05:31.640 --> 05:36.800
So we are at the center of this kind of continuum that stretches in two different timescales,

05:36.800 --> 05:42.640
but it's actually even more complex than that, because now with bioengineering and various

05:42.640 --> 05:48.800
other technologies, there are additional axes in this space where we can stretch the notion

05:48.800 --> 05:50.440
of what a human actually is.

05:50.440 --> 05:55.200
And you can imagine slowly adding various prosthetics, various technologies within the

05:55.200 --> 06:01.400
body as is already happening, people who can control wheelchairs with their minds via implants

06:01.400 --> 06:02.400
and things like this.

06:02.400 --> 06:08.800
And of course, biological modifications that we can make both genetic and non-genetic.

06:08.800 --> 06:13.720
And so we see here that and at every level of organization, cell tissue organism and

06:13.720 --> 06:22.240
so on, we can replace native naturally evolved materials with all sorts of novel, either

06:22.240 --> 06:24.760
natural or engineered materials.

06:24.760 --> 06:32.560
And so we start to see that this notion of a standard human can be quite continuous in

06:32.560 --> 06:34.240
a number of different dimensions.

06:34.240 --> 06:40.360
And so I've been trying to develop a framework called TAME, and we'll talk about this more.

06:40.360 --> 06:43.680
TAME stands for technological approach to mind everywhere.

06:43.680 --> 06:51.880
And the idea is to be able to recognize, create, and relate to truly diverse intelligences,

06:51.880 --> 06:58.040
not just the familiar creatures like us and maybe birds and dolphins and things, but also

06:58.040 --> 07:03.520
really unusual creatures like colonial organisms and swarms and synthetic life forms that might

07:03.520 --> 07:11.280
be engineered, software artificial intelligences, possible alien life if that's found.

07:11.280 --> 07:17.240
So all of these things ought to be able to be handled by a mature science of diverse

07:17.240 --> 07:18.400
intelligence.

07:18.400 --> 07:23.400
And they have to be dealt with the same set of concepts regardless of what they're made

07:23.400 --> 07:29.120
of, so regardless of their composition or origin story, meaning evolved versus engineered

07:29.120 --> 07:30.720
or anything in between.

07:30.720 --> 07:33.840
And of course, I'm not the first person to try for something like this.

07:33.840 --> 07:38.480
So Rosenbluth, Wiener, and Bigelow did something like this.

07:38.480 --> 07:43.520
In the 40s where they gave us this ladder, where you can see that all the way from basically

07:43.520 --> 07:49.400
passive matter, all the way up through complex human metacognitive types of capacities, there

07:49.400 --> 07:52.520
are a set of great transitions.

07:52.520 --> 07:55.640
But nevertheless, these things are all on the same spectrum.

07:55.640 --> 08:02.680
The idea was that we should be able to understand how various types of material implementations

08:02.680 --> 08:07.000
can begin to have these kinds of functionalities.

08:07.000 --> 08:15.120
And so one of the essential ways of thinking about these things in my framework has to do

08:15.120 --> 08:17.560
with the relation of an observer.

08:17.560 --> 08:21.760
And that observer might be an engineer, it might be another conspecific, it might be some

08:21.760 --> 08:27.720
sort of a parasite or in fact, the evolutionary process itself, some sort of observer that

08:27.720 --> 08:31.320
is able to modulate what the system is doing.

08:31.320 --> 08:36.440
And so you can think about different ways of modulating a system depending on how sophisticated

08:36.440 --> 08:37.440
it is.

08:37.440 --> 08:40.800
So down here on this end of the spectrum, the only way you're going to make changes is

08:40.800 --> 08:43.600
by engineering directly at the hardware level.

08:43.600 --> 08:47.440
You're not going to convince a clock of anything, you're not going to reward and punish it.

08:47.440 --> 08:49.760
All there is is mechanical engineering.

08:49.760 --> 08:54.280
But you can cybernetics take this to things like this, these thermostats which have recorded

08:54.280 --> 08:55.280
set points.

08:55.280 --> 08:59.880
And so there you can do some interesting things such as modify the set point without rewiring

08:59.880 --> 09:04.320
the hardware and get the system to take on a novel set of goals without having to rewire

09:04.320 --> 09:05.320
it.

09:05.320 --> 09:09.160
And then of course, more complex systems, availous of an interface involving rewards

09:09.160 --> 09:14.200
and punishments and various other behavior shaping techniques where you can rely on the

09:14.200 --> 09:16.560
system to learn from experience.

09:16.560 --> 09:20.960
And then of course, we have even more, even more complex beings which are able to follow

09:20.960 --> 09:22.320
logic and so on.

09:22.320 --> 09:27.280
And so the difference in all of these different systems is not what they're made of or how

09:27.280 --> 09:32.440
they got here, but it's what are the set of tools and techniques that you might use to

09:32.440 --> 09:36.800
relate to that system all the way from physical rewiring to something that looks a lot more

09:36.800 --> 09:42.040
like a psychoanalysis where you're literally trying to affect the model that the system

09:42.040 --> 09:44.920
has of itself, of the outside world and so on.

09:44.920 --> 09:52.400
So this shows you the kind of inclusive framework we're trying to make.

09:52.400 --> 09:57.200
And the interesting thing is that all of us made this amazing journey across the Cartesian

09:57.200 --> 09:58.200
cut.

09:58.200 --> 10:04.000
We were all ones, so-called just physics, physics and chemistry, a little blob of protoplasm

10:04.000 --> 10:07.360
and an unfertilized oocyte, quiescent.

10:07.360 --> 10:12.280
And then through the process of embryonic development, we became one of these functional

10:12.280 --> 10:15.560
creatures or even something like this.

10:15.560 --> 10:24.960
And the crucial thing about this process of self-construction is that there is no magical

10:24.960 --> 10:30.800
sort of sharp red line at which point you go from being just physics to being a true

10:30.800 --> 10:32.120
cognitive being.

10:32.120 --> 10:36.840
So many people would like to look at themselves and say, we have true, you name it, sentience,

10:36.840 --> 10:40.240
cognition, intelligence, whatever term you want.

10:40.240 --> 10:44.560
And then they would look at something like this, which is a little blob of chemicals.

10:44.560 --> 10:47.040
And they say, well, that certainly doesn't have any of those things.

10:47.040 --> 10:51.280
And so then you owe a story of how you got from here to there.

10:51.280 --> 10:56.360
And that story cannot be any kind of a sharp change.

10:56.360 --> 11:02.160
It has to be a gradual process that is in concert with what we know about embryonic development

11:02.160 --> 11:03.660
and so on.

11:03.660 --> 11:04.660
So that's interesting.

11:04.660 --> 11:09.120
So we go from matter to mind in this way that I think developmental biology is maybe the

11:09.440 --> 11:11.680
most magical of the sciences.

11:11.680 --> 11:14.960
But at least we tend to think of ourselves, once we get here, we tend to think of ourselves

11:14.960 --> 11:19.240
as some sort of a unified intelligence.

11:19.240 --> 11:24.160
And in fact, we often, people will contrast the kinds of thing that we are with something

11:24.160 --> 11:29.760
like ant colonies or bee swarms or something like that and say, well, we talk about that

11:29.760 --> 11:32.640
as a collective intelligence, but that's a metaphor.

11:32.640 --> 11:36.520
We are a true intelligence, collective intelligence is something else.

11:36.520 --> 11:39.680
But actually, this is not the case.

11:39.680 --> 11:43.880
And so Descartes, for example, was really interested in the pineal gland because he said that the

11:43.880 --> 11:50.000
pineal gland was unique, it was an unpaired organ in the brain and therefore a kind of

11:50.000 --> 11:54.480
a singular unified location for the mind to interact with the body.

11:54.480 --> 11:58.160
But if he had had access to good microscopy, what he would have discovered is that there

11:58.160 --> 12:00.360
isn't one of anything in the brain.

12:00.360 --> 12:04.120
In fact, inside the pineal gland, you see this, which is a huge number of individual

12:04.120 --> 12:05.440
cells.

12:06.080 --> 12:09.680
If he had had this technology, he could have looked inside of any one of those cells and

12:09.680 --> 12:14.040
discovered that they, in fact, are made of a huge number of different components and

12:14.040 --> 12:15.440
various kinds of active matter.

12:15.440 --> 12:21.520
So there are mitochondria, there are little motors that zip up and down various filaments,

12:21.520 --> 12:23.760
just an incredible number of parts.

12:23.760 --> 12:27.360
And so all of us are collective intelligences.

12:27.360 --> 12:33.240
I'm not aware of any intelligence that is really just some sort of one indivisible diamond

12:33.240 --> 12:34.560
of mind.

12:34.560 --> 12:37.040
We are all made of parts of different kinds.

12:37.040 --> 12:39.600
And so this is the sort of thing we're made of.

12:39.600 --> 12:42.400
This is a single cell, it's called the lacrimaria.

12:42.400 --> 12:45.640
This is a unicellular organism.

12:45.640 --> 12:48.840
It has no brain, it has no nervous system, no stem cells.

12:48.840 --> 12:57.120
It has remarkable competencies over its physiological, metabolic, and anatomical goals.

12:57.120 --> 13:02.920
So you can see here that it's basically, this is at hunting in its environment.

13:02.920 --> 13:06.800
If you're into soft-body robotics, this is an amazing design challenge.

13:06.800 --> 13:10.760
We don't have anything remotely this competent.

13:10.760 --> 13:13.800
And cells have all kinds of other interesting capabilities.

13:13.800 --> 13:17.560
So this is the sort of thing that's studied in the field of diverse intelligence or basal

13:17.560 --> 13:18.560
cognition.

13:18.560 --> 13:20.680
I'll show you another example.

13:20.680 --> 13:22.600
This is a slime mold.

13:22.600 --> 13:26.560
So this slime mold, this is a unicellular slime mold called physarum polycephalum.

13:26.560 --> 13:29.120
And we've put a little bit of it here on this petri dish.

13:29.120 --> 13:31.240
We put one glass disc up here.

13:31.240 --> 13:33.080
We put three glass discs back here.

13:33.080 --> 13:34.080
They're just glass.

13:34.080 --> 13:35.080
They're completely inert.

13:35.080 --> 13:36.080
They're very thin.

13:36.080 --> 13:38.880
They have no food or any kind of a chemical substance on them.

13:38.880 --> 13:43.880
But what happens is that this, and by the way, this slime mold, it's a single cell.

13:43.880 --> 13:46.200
It can be very large, but the whole thing is a single cell.

13:46.200 --> 13:50.840
So what it starts to do is it starts to grow out, basically in every direction at once.

13:50.840 --> 13:56.000
But during this time, during these 600 minutes or so, what it's actually doing as we discovered

13:56.000 --> 14:00.600
is gently tugging on the material around it and reading the strain angle that comes

14:00.600 --> 14:01.600
back.

14:01.600 --> 14:07.120
And based on that strain angle, it builds up towards a decision of where the heavier

14:07.120 --> 14:08.280
mass is.

14:08.280 --> 14:11.720
And the way we know this is because reliably what it's going to do is grow towards the

14:11.720 --> 14:12.960
heavier mass.

14:12.960 --> 14:17.520
And so by reading that strain angle, it's able to gain some knowledge of its environment.

14:17.520 --> 14:22.360
And then for some reason that we don't know, it prefers moving towards the heavier masses.

14:22.360 --> 14:28.800
And so we see that we have this biological material that's very sort of ancient and early

14:28.800 --> 14:32.160
in life has interesting capabilities.

14:32.160 --> 14:37.040
And then the real question becomes, how do these things scale up?

14:37.040 --> 14:41.480
What is it that allows combinations of these cells to do something like this?

14:41.480 --> 14:44.760
So this is a very standard scenario.

14:44.760 --> 14:50.920
The rat learns to press the lever to get the reward, and that's sort of very well understood.

14:50.920 --> 14:56.600
But the interesting thing is that the rat is really a collection of cells, and no individual

14:56.600 --> 14:59.000
cell has both experiences.

14:59.000 --> 15:02.720
So there are cells on the foot of the rat that interact with the lever.

15:02.720 --> 15:08.440
There are cells in the intestine that collect the nutritious reward sometime later.

15:08.440 --> 15:13.000
But no individual cell has the experience of doing this and receiving that.

15:13.000 --> 15:18.360
And so who is it that owns this kind of associative memory between two events that no individual

15:18.360 --> 15:19.360
cell experienced?

15:19.360 --> 15:24.160
So clearly, you need some sort of a, and the standard answer, of course, is the nervous

15:24.160 --> 15:29.720
system provides this, you need some sort of way to integrate individual cellular activities

15:29.720 --> 15:31.720
towards a single being.

15:31.720 --> 15:33.600
Now this is kind of very common.

15:33.600 --> 15:39.560
I want to show you some uncommon examples that people don't hear about a lot to kind

15:39.560 --> 15:42.600
of stretch our idea of what's possible.

15:42.600 --> 15:49.160
So this is a caterpillar, a soft-bodied kind of creature that crawls around and eats leaves,

15:49.160 --> 15:51.320
and it has a certain kind of brain.

15:51.320 --> 15:55.320
Remarkably, it transforms itself into a completely different kind of creature that now lives

15:55.320 --> 15:56.680
in a three-dimensional world.

15:56.680 --> 16:00.040
It flies, and it doesn't like leaves anymore.

16:00.040 --> 16:01.040
It wants nectar.

16:01.040 --> 16:05.000
And so a very different set of behaviors, very different set of preferences, very different

16:05.000 --> 16:06.760
brain.

16:06.760 --> 16:10.640
The brain is actually largely dissolved during this metamorphosis process.

16:10.640 --> 16:14.600
The most of the synapses are broken, maybe most of the cells are killed, and a new brain

16:14.600 --> 16:15.920
is reassembled.

16:15.920 --> 16:22.560
But there's actually really good evidence that the memories that you impart onto the

16:22.560 --> 16:27.560
caterpillar that you train, the moth or butterfly will actually retain those memories, and there's

16:27.560 --> 16:31.840
work on this in beetles and various other creatures.

16:31.840 --> 16:33.720
So you can think about two things.

16:33.720 --> 16:38.960
The practical issue of, isn't it amazing to have a memory medium that can basically be

16:38.960 --> 16:44.320
taken apart and put back together and drastically rearranged and still retain its information

16:44.320 --> 16:45.320
content?

16:45.320 --> 16:50.480
Anything like that in computer science or anything like that.

16:50.480 --> 16:54.360
And of course, it raises some philosophical, interesting philosophical questions, which

16:54.360 --> 16:59.200
is, never mind the older question of what's it like to be a butterfly, the question could

16:59.200 --> 17:04.120
be posed, what's it like to be a caterpillar slowly changing into a butterfly?

17:04.120 --> 17:08.040
Because this is a change that happens not on an evolutionary time scale, but actually

17:08.040 --> 17:10.880
during the lifetime of an active individual.

17:10.880 --> 17:18.600
And so this ability to retain memory through very drastic deformations is really maximized

17:18.600 --> 17:21.640
by this other system known as planarian flatworms.

17:21.640 --> 17:23.880
We'll talk much more about that.

17:23.880 --> 17:30.520
And these planarian flatworms, they can be trained, and if you train them, for example,

17:30.520 --> 17:36.920
to recognize these little bumpy patterns as the place where they get fed, what you can

17:36.920 --> 17:42.400
then do is amputate their head, which contains their brain.

17:42.400 --> 17:46.840
You are left with a tail, the tail sits there doing nothing for about eight days.

17:46.840 --> 17:53.080
It slowly regrows a brand new head and McConnell, who discovered this in the 60s and got a lot

17:53.080 --> 17:57.720
of flak for it was actually completely correct in that these new animals with a brand new

17:57.720 --> 18:01.200
brain still remember that original information.

18:01.200 --> 18:06.480
And so what we have here is first evidence that information is not stored exclusively

18:06.480 --> 18:10.760
in their centralized brain, but actually apparently spread throughout the body.

18:10.760 --> 18:18.160
And you see this ability of those tissues to imprint that information onto the new brain

18:18.160 --> 18:19.160
as it develops.

18:19.160 --> 18:23.200
So this idea of information actually moving through body tissue.

18:23.200 --> 18:27.160
And so you can think about, you know, there's this malfunctioning transporter experiment

18:27.160 --> 18:30.560
from philosophy 101 where they say, well, there's this transporter.

18:30.560 --> 18:34.680
And so what it does is you step into it and it destroys the original body and recreates

18:34.680 --> 18:36.760
a molecule for molecule copy somewhere else.

18:36.760 --> 18:40.600
And so now you've you've transported, but what if it malfunctions and it doesn't erase

18:40.600 --> 18:41.600
the original copy?

18:41.600 --> 18:42.600
How many of you are there?

18:42.600 --> 18:47.080
Well, in Plenaria, you can literally do that because you can cut them into into pieces,

18:47.080 --> 18:51.080
many pieces, and each piece becomes a perfect little little worm.

18:51.080 --> 18:57.080
So so so we start to see that that, you know, kind of the common workhorses of behavioral

18:57.080 --> 19:01.480
science and cognitive neuroscience or rats and things like this are just the tip of the

19:01.480 --> 19:02.480
iceberg.

19:02.480 --> 19:07.280
And there are many interesting phenomena that speak to this question of what are cells,

19:07.280 --> 19:13.320
what are integrated beings, what what's information, how does it move through the body invertebrates.

19:13.320 --> 19:15.600
