01:32:52.100 --> 01:32:54.260
and you could have these very large light cones.

01:32:54.260 --> 01:32:56.940
And by the way, you have the added psychological pressure

01:32:56.940 --> 01:32:59.500
of knowing for a fact that some of your goals

01:32:59.500 --> 01:33:01.980
are not achievable in your lifetime

01:33:01.980 --> 01:33:03.820
because your cognitive light cone is bigger

01:33:03.820 --> 01:33:08.580
than your actual survival, your possible survival.

01:33:08.580 --> 01:33:10.420
So if you're a goldfish, you don't have that problem.

01:33:10.420 --> 01:33:14.900
All your goals are achievable in your lifetime

01:33:14.900 --> 01:33:17.940
because they're all very kind of short path.

01:33:17.940 --> 01:33:22.140
And of course, as maybe it was Beth or somebody had pointed out

01:33:22.140 --> 01:33:25.620
that we are of course compound intelligences

01:33:25.620 --> 01:33:27.140
because we are made of components

01:33:27.140 --> 01:33:28.940
with their own little cognitive light cones

01:33:28.940 --> 01:33:30.180
in their own spaces.

01:33:30.180 --> 01:33:34.820
So we are this huge patchwork of compound intelligences

01:33:34.820 --> 01:33:38.220
all of which see different worlds in different spaces

01:33:38.220 --> 01:33:40.580
and are all cooperating and competing and so on

01:33:40.580 --> 01:33:42.620
both across and within levels.

01:33:42.620 --> 01:33:44.140
So with this notion,

01:33:44.180 --> 01:33:45.540
let's think about a few things.

01:33:45.540 --> 01:33:48.300
First of all, let's go back to this idea

01:33:48.300 --> 01:33:49.780
of a collective intelligence.

01:33:49.780 --> 01:33:54.780
So if somebody shows you a human brain,

01:33:55.260 --> 01:33:57.900
if you didn't already know what a human look like

01:33:57.900 --> 01:33:58.980
and maybe even if you did

01:33:58.980 --> 01:34:00.500
because it's not an obvious question

01:34:00.500 --> 01:34:03.100
and somebody asks you, how many individuals are in there?

01:34:03.100 --> 01:34:05.100
How many selves are in there?

01:34:05.100 --> 01:34:08.660
And it leads to the fact that we do not know actually

01:34:08.660 --> 01:34:10.900
how much brain matter it takes

01:34:10.900 --> 01:34:13.260
to support a single human self.

01:34:13.260 --> 01:34:15.340
I mean, we see the normal case,

01:34:15.340 --> 01:34:18.340
but this leads to people saying things like,

01:34:18.340 --> 01:34:20.540
wow, with such a, for a B or something like that

01:34:20.540 --> 01:34:22.500
with such a tiny brain, it does a,

01:34:22.500 --> 01:34:26.620
well, we don't know how much it takes to be a single self.

01:34:26.620 --> 01:34:28.740
We don't have any way of guessing what that's gonna be

01:34:28.740 --> 01:34:30.580
until you already know what a human is.

01:34:30.580 --> 01:34:32.460
So let's look at this example.

01:34:32.460 --> 01:34:36.020
This is a schematic of an early blastoderm

01:34:36.020 --> 01:34:40.260
of an amniote embryo, let's say it's a bird or a human.

01:34:40.260 --> 01:34:41.660
And what you see is a bunch of cells.

01:34:41.660 --> 01:34:44.420
There's 50,000 cells and we look at that

01:34:44.420 --> 01:34:46.620
and we say, oh, there's an embryo.

01:34:46.620 --> 01:34:48.220
Now, what are we counting when we say

01:34:48.220 --> 01:34:49.460
there's one embryo there?

01:34:49.460 --> 01:34:50.900
What is there one of?

01:34:50.900 --> 01:34:52.740
There are tens of thousands of cells.

01:34:52.740 --> 01:34:53.940
What is there one of?

01:34:53.940 --> 01:34:56.380
What we're actually counting is alignment.

01:34:56.380 --> 01:34:58.380
We're counting the fact that all of these,

01:34:58.380 --> 01:35:00.100
and that alignment is literal

01:35:00.100 --> 01:35:02.180
because the cells physically have to align with each other

01:35:02.180 --> 01:35:04.800
and also alignment in morphogenetic space

01:35:04.800 --> 01:35:07.100
because all of these cells normally

01:35:07.100 --> 01:35:10.060
are going to work together to build one individual.

01:35:10.060 --> 01:35:11.940
They have one particular large scale pattern

01:35:11.940 --> 01:35:12.940
that they're all going to build

01:35:12.940 --> 01:35:15.300
and that is what we're counting as one.

01:35:15.300 --> 01:35:18.660
And now, could you guess in advance

01:35:18.660 --> 01:35:20.540
how many embryos there are

01:35:20.540 --> 01:35:23.020
or how many individuals are in this brain?

01:35:23.020 --> 01:35:25.020
It's a very similar as I was saying before

01:35:25.020 --> 01:35:27.740
with the Turing, the kind of allusion to Turing.

01:35:27.740 --> 01:35:29.700
It's a very similar problem.

01:35:29.700 --> 01:35:31.900
Can you tell how many are going to be in there?

01:35:31.900 --> 01:35:34.040
Is it genetically specified how many are in there?

01:35:34.040 --> 01:35:35.700
Well, the answer is it is not.

01:35:35.700 --> 01:35:39.940
So here's an experiment that Lutz first did

01:35:39.940 --> 01:35:42.220
in the 40s and I used to do as a grad student

01:35:42.220 --> 01:35:43.860
in the duck embryo.

01:35:43.860 --> 01:35:46.060
So what you can do is you can take a little needle

01:35:46.060 --> 01:35:48.860
and you can put some scratches in this blastoderm.

01:35:48.860 --> 01:35:50.120
And so what happens is that once you,

01:35:50.120 --> 01:35:51.980
when you made those little scratches

01:35:51.980 --> 01:35:53.700
until they heal up, which they will,

01:35:53.700 --> 01:35:56.400
but until they heal up, every region

01:35:56.400 --> 01:35:59.360
which does not feel the presence of these other regions

01:35:59.360 --> 01:36:00.220
becomes an embryo.

01:36:00.220 --> 01:36:03.200
It self-organizes an embryo and then it heals.

01:36:03.200 --> 01:36:05.640
And then what you have is multiple areas

01:36:05.640 --> 01:36:07.980
that are conjoined twins or triplets.

01:36:07.980 --> 01:36:09.420
And then in between them,

01:36:09.420 --> 01:36:11.660
you have these little weird little disputed zones

01:36:11.660 --> 01:36:13.820
where these cells can't quite tell who they belong to,

01:36:13.820 --> 01:36:15.220
but in the end they have to make a decision

01:36:15.220 --> 01:36:17.220
and they become part of this or part of that.

01:36:17.220 --> 01:36:21.500
And this is really, there are a couple

01:36:21.500 --> 01:36:22.340
of interesting things here.

01:36:22.340 --> 01:36:24.260
First of all, because of this,

01:36:24.260 --> 01:36:28.500
because you can split this up into some number of islands,

01:36:28.500 --> 01:36:31.580
the number of cells, just imagine this is a human embryo,

01:36:31.580 --> 01:36:35.020
the number of individuals in there is not fixed.

01:36:35.020 --> 01:36:37.380
It is not determined by the genetics.

01:36:37.380 --> 01:36:40.820
It is set in real time by the physiology.

01:36:40.820 --> 01:36:43.060
It could be zero, it could be one, it could be two,

01:36:43.060 --> 01:36:45.860
it could be some number of embryos,

01:36:45.860 --> 01:36:47.700
probably up to half a dozen, let's say.

01:36:48.780 --> 01:36:53.780
And it's very important for the making of cells

01:36:55.140 --> 01:36:57.340
that they are self-organized,

01:36:57.340 --> 01:36:58.580
meaning that they don't know,

01:36:58.580 --> 01:37:00.780
each cell does not know where it,

01:37:00.780 --> 01:37:05.080
where every cell is some other cells external environment.

01:37:05.080 --> 01:37:07.680
So where do I end and my neighbor begins?

01:37:07.680 --> 01:37:10.720
Or where do I end and the outside world begins?

01:37:10.720 --> 01:37:11.960
This is something that is not true

01:37:11.960 --> 01:37:15.920
for almost any current AI or robotic system,

01:37:15.920 --> 01:37:17.920
because they don't have to put themselves together

01:37:17.920 --> 01:37:19.880
from scratch, they are told right from the beginning,

01:37:19.880 --> 01:37:20.720
they're programmed to say,

01:37:20.720 --> 01:37:22.080
this is your border, here are the inputs,

01:37:22.080 --> 01:37:23.920
here are the outputs, you are here,

01:37:23.920 --> 01:37:25.200
the outside world is there.

01:37:25.200 --> 01:37:26.920
That is not the case for living beings.

01:37:26.920 --> 01:37:30.720
We have to self-construct and we do not know right away

01:37:30.720 --> 01:37:32.840
where our borders are, how many of us are in there

01:37:32.840 --> 01:37:33.680
and so on.

01:37:34.680 --> 01:37:37.080
This also taking it back to the brain, of course,

01:37:37.080 --> 01:37:39.200
is this issue of individuation,

01:37:39.200 --> 01:37:41.880
because in split brain patients

01:37:41.880 --> 01:37:43.680
and dissociative disorders and so on,

01:37:43.680 --> 01:37:46.840
you find out that there actually are more than one self

01:37:46.840 --> 01:37:48.520
within a standard human brain,

01:37:48.520 --> 01:37:50.800
how many could fit in there, we do not know,

01:37:50.800 --> 01:37:54.320
but the record for these dissociative kind of cases,

01:37:54.320 --> 01:37:57.120
I mean, I think I've read in the 60s,

01:37:57.120 --> 01:37:59.360
60 different personalities that could be in there.

01:37:59.440 --> 01:38:03.840
So this idea of an active medium,

01:38:03.840 --> 01:38:06.960
an excitable medium that differentiates

01:38:06.960 --> 01:38:11.960
into a number of coherent selves is really key.

01:38:12.680 --> 01:38:15.240
And so now you have to start asking yourself, okay,

01:38:15.240 --> 01:38:19.680
so as we are self-constructing out of this,

01:38:19.680 --> 01:38:22.960
sort of this Freudian ocean of possibility,

01:38:22.960 --> 01:38:25.480
some out of 20 or 50,000 cells,

01:38:25.480 --> 01:38:27.680
three or two or one embryo will form,

01:38:28.520 --> 01:38:33.120
what are the dynamics that actually allow individual cells

01:38:33.120 --> 01:38:34.960
with their own tiny little goals,

01:38:34.960 --> 01:38:36.080
what are the goals of cells?

01:38:36.080 --> 01:38:38.000
Well, every cell wants to become two cells

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:39.440
and they have metabolic goals

01:38:39.440 --> 01:38:40.760
that they try to meet and so on.

01:38:40.760 --> 01:38:42.800
What allows them to scale up

01:38:42.800 --> 01:38:47.800
to work towards very sort of a large complex goals

01:38:48.680 --> 01:38:49.760
like building a whole embryo?

01:38:49.760 --> 01:38:50.600
I mean, that's huge.

01:38:50.600 --> 01:38:52.760
No individual cell can know what a whole embryo is,

01:38:52.760 --> 01:38:53.880
but the collective does.

01:38:53.880 --> 01:38:55.320
So what allows that?

01:38:55.320 --> 01:38:56.440
Well, here are some hypotheses.

01:38:56.440 --> 01:38:58.680
One thing that allows it, I think,

01:38:58.680 --> 01:39:00.960
is the kind of memory wiping that happens

01:39:00.960 --> 01:39:03.040
when cells are electrically connected.

01:39:03.040 --> 01:39:04.760
Because when two cells signal each other

01:39:04.760 --> 01:39:05.600
the old-fashioned way,

01:39:05.600 --> 01:39:07.720
where they just sort of secrete a chemical molecule

01:39:07.720 --> 01:39:09.680
and it comes over here and the cell senses it,

01:39:09.680 --> 01:39:11.240
it's very easy for this cell to know

01:39:11.240 --> 01:39:13.720
whether that signal came from the outside or not.

01:39:13.720 --> 01:39:14.680
So they can maintain,

01:39:14.680 --> 01:39:16.680
these two cells can maintain their individuality

01:39:16.680 --> 01:39:18.400
and they can maintain different memories

01:39:18.400 --> 01:39:19.920
and the cell can ignore the signal

01:39:19.920 --> 01:39:22.320
or do something about it, whatever.

01:39:22.320 --> 01:39:24.040
But there's something magic

01:39:24.040 --> 01:39:25.560
about these electrical gap junctions.

01:39:25.560 --> 01:39:28.600
When the cells are joined by these gap junctions,

01:39:28.600 --> 01:39:32.360
this signal, let's say it's a calcium spike

01:39:32.360 --> 01:39:33.200
from being injured.

01:39:33.200 --> 01:39:34.600
This cell got poked with something

01:39:34.600 --> 01:39:37.440
and this calcium spike is a trace of that event,

01:39:37.440 --> 01:39:39.320
a kind of a memory n-gram of that event.

01:39:39.320 --> 01:39:42.080
It will immediately propagate through these gap junctions

01:39:42.080 --> 01:39:45.480
and that the interpretation of that signal for this cell

01:39:47.440 --> 01:39:49.840
is exactly the same as it would before

01:39:49.840 --> 01:39:51.400
its own calcium spike.

01:39:51.400 --> 01:39:53.440
Calcium doesn't have any metadata on it

01:39:53.440 --> 01:39:54.960
that says, where did you come from?

01:39:55.000 --> 01:39:56.640
So by moving through this,

01:39:56.640 --> 01:39:58.520
there's a kind of memory,

01:39:58.520 --> 01:40:00.800
kind of identity wipe that happens

01:40:00.800 --> 01:40:03.080
where this cell now has that same memory trace.

01:40:03.080 --> 01:40:04.320
And as far as it's concerned,

01:40:04.320 --> 01:40:05.800
that's its own natural memory.

01:40:05.800 --> 01:40:08.280
It has no way of knowing that's a false memory.

01:40:08.280 --> 01:40:10.240
So to this cell, that's a false memory,

01:40:10.240 --> 01:40:11.560
but to the collective,

01:40:11.560 --> 01:40:14.840
it is an absolutely true memory that the collective had.

01:40:14.840 --> 01:40:17.000
So that kind of wiping property,

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:19.160
it strips ownership information.

01:40:19.160 --> 01:40:22.320
It makes it very hard for each cell

01:40:22.320 --> 01:40:24.320
to maintain an individual identity

01:40:24.320 --> 01:40:26.040
with respect to what its history was.

01:40:26.040 --> 01:40:28.640
And it makes collectives out of individual cells.

01:40:28.640 --> 01:40:30.760
And of course it makes them bigger.

01:40:30.760 --> 01:40:32.760
So my memory become our memories,

01:40:32.760 --> 01:40:35.040
my stress state becomes our stress

01:40:35.040 --> 01:40:37.000
and my goal becomes our goal.

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:41.040
And so by when a single cell in this diagram,

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:44.240
when a single cell has some size of a cognitive light going

01:40:44.240 --> 01:40:46.800
and some ability to anticipate and remember,

01:40:46.800 --> 01:40:51.800
a network of these cells has a bigger computational capacity

01:40:52.320 --> 01:40:54.840
and a bigger spatial sensorium.

01:40:54.840 --> 01:40:57.440
And it can actually have larger scale,

01:40:57.440 --> 01:41:00.360
more complex states as set points.

01:41:00.360 --> 01:41:02.320
And now you can start to see how a collection of cells

01:41:02.320 --> 01:41:04.320
could actually work on something like building an arm

01:41:04.320 --> 01:41:06.000
or building a whole body.

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:07.240
And so we can imagine,

01:41:07.240 --> 01:41:08.360
and so we're doing this now

01:41:08.360 --> 01:41:12.240
is doing these very specific computational models

01:41:12.240 --> 01:41:15.760
of how little tiny homeostatic loops like this,

01:41:15.760 --> 01:41:19.160
for example, measure the pH and act

01:41:19.160 --> 01:41:21.920
become very large homeostatic loops

01:41:21.920 --> 01:41:23.280
about something completely different.

01:41:23.280 --> 01:41:25.960
Single cells cannot remember anything like this,

01:41:25.960 --> 01:41:28.840
but a giant collection of cells could.

01:41:28.840 --> 01:41:30.720
And so this is a very active area of research

01:41:30.720 --> 01:41:33.760
is to figure out exactly how that scales up.

01:41:33.760 --> 01:41:36.760
The implications are these,

01:41:36.760 --> 01:41:38.240
here's what evolution has done.

01:41:38.240 --> 01:41:41.200
Evolution has enabled single cells to work together

01:41:41.200 --> 01:41:43.320
to enlarge their cognitive light cones

01:41:43.320 --> 01:41:47.240
where the goals scale from the very humble goals

01:41:47.280 --> 01:41:51.040
of single cells to the more grandiose goals of collectives

01:41:51.040 --> 01:41:52.960
where they can work on something gigantic

01:41:52.960 --> 01:41:54.640
like making sure you have four fingers.

01:41:54.640 --> 01:41:56.560
This cell doesn't know anything about what a finger is,

01:41:56.560 --> 01:41:58.440
but this collective does.

01:41:58.440 --> 01:42:00.080
So evolution gave us the scale up,

01:42:00.080 --> 01:42:01.800
but there's a failure mode to this.

01:42:01.800 --> 01:42:03.200
The failure mode is cancer.

01:42:03.200 --> 01:42:06.520
So here's where when these cells

01:42:06.520 --> 01:42:08.880
are electrically isolated from each other,

01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:12.080
this is human glioblastoma in culture.

01:42:12.080 --> 01:42:14.000
So these individual cells can roll back

01:42:14.000 --> 01:42:16.760
to their unicellular past.

01:42:16.760 --> 01:42:18.360
They do not become more selfish.

01:42:18.360 --> 01:42:20.800
A lot of game theory kind of approaches

01:42:20.800 --> 01:42:22.800
treat cancer cells as more selfish.

01:42:22.800 --> 01:42:24.120
They don't become more selfish.

01:42:24.120 --> 01:42:25.760
Their cells get smaller.

01:42:25.760 --> 01:42:26.600
They're just a selfish.

01:42:26.600 --> 01:42:28.440
It's just that the self here is huge.

01:42:28.440 --> 01:42:32.040
Their self is very tiny and they do the best they can.

01:42:32.040 --> 01:42:36.360
But biometically, if you have that kind of weird perspective

01:42:36.360 --> 01:42:39.920
on cancer as a disorder of selfhood,

01:42:39.920 --> 01:42:42.320
then what you can do is something interesting.

01:42:42.320 --> 01:42:44.720
And we did this years ago.

01:42:45.720 --> 01:42:48.880
You can induce tumors using human oncogenes,

01:42:48.880 --> 01:42:50.720
but what you can do is use these ion channels

01:42:50.720 --> 01:42:53.440
to force the cells to be in the correct electrical state

01:42:53.440 --> 01:42:55.520
to maintain proper communication.

01:42:55.520 --> 01:42:57.920
And when you do that, even though the oncogene is blazingly

01:42:57.920 --> 01:42:59.200
expressed, it's labeled in red here.

01:42:59.200 --> 01:43:00.760
You can see it's all over the place.

01:43:00.760 --> 01:43:01.440
There's no tumor.

01:43:01.440 --> 01:43:02.640
This is the same animal.

01:43:02.640 --> 01:43:06.280
There's no tumor because the genetics might have a defect.

01:43:06.280 --> 01:43:08.080
The hardware might be a little bit broken.

01:43:08.080 --> 01:43:10.520
But as long as the cell is physiologically

01:43:10.520 --> 01:43:13.520
part of this network that contains large scale

01:43:13.520 --> 01:43:16.720
goals like building nice skin, nice muscle, and so on,

01:43:16.720 --> 01:43:18.760
they're kept away from tumorogenesis

01:43:18.760 --> 01:43:22.880
and harness towards these large scale anatomical goals.

01:43:22.880 --> 01:43:27.800
So the last piece I want to show you, it goes beyond this.

01:43:27.800 --> 01:43:30.640
So we've been talking about goals in different spaces.

01:43:30.640 --> 01:43:33.760
So the tiny metabolic goals of single cells,

01:43:33.760 --> 01:43:37.560
the morphogenetic goals of cellular collectives.

01:43:37.560 --> 01:43:40.680
And now we can ask the following question.

01:43:40.680 --> 01:43:42.360
Where do these goals come from?

01:43:42.360 --> 01:43:45.760
And what other goals can novel beings have?

01:43:45.760 --> 01:43:47.480
And so this is a project that I also

01:43:47.480 --> 01:43:51.040
have to do a disclosure here because Josh Bongard and I

01:43:51.040 --> 01:43:53.200
have another company called Fauna Systems, which is all

01:43:53.200 --> 01:43:56.520
about AI-designed biorebotics.

01:43:56.520 --> 01:43:59.280
And this is all work done in collaboration

01:43:59.280 --> 01:44:02.680
with a Bongard lab at this Institute of Computationally

01:44:02.680 --> 01:44:04.520
Designed Organisms.

01:44:04.520 --> 01:44:08.120
We asked the following question, how much plasticity

01:44:08.120 --> 01:44:09.000
do these cells have?

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:11.040
And when they're liberated from their normal boundary

01:44:11.040 --> 01:44:14.040
conditions of the animal, what will they do?

01:44:14.040 --> 01:44:15.920
How will they reboot multicellularity?

01:44:15.920 --> 01:44:19.120
How will they navigate anatomical and behavioral spaces?

01:44:19.120 --> 01:44:20.160
What can they do?

01:44:20.160 --> 01:44:22.240
So here's the experiment.

01:44:22.240 --> 01:44:24.720
And all the biology here was done by Douglas Blackest

01:44:24.720 --> 01:44:26.280
and the staff scientists in the group.

01:44:26.280 --> 01:44:28.520
What we did was we took an early frog embryo.

01:44:28.520 --> 01:44:33.480
And at this stage, where they have about 1,000 cells or so,

01:44:33.480 --> 01:44:39.000
we cut off these cells up here, which are the skin.

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:41.960
This is all faded to be skin cells.

01:44:41.960 --> 01:44:45.920
And we dissociated them and we put them back

01:44:45.920 --> 01:44:48.000
in this little depression here.

01:44:48.000 --> 01:44:49.560
And so they're just skin.

01:44:49.560 --> 01:44:50.080
There's no nerve.

01:44:50.080 --> 01:44:51.800
There's no muscle, just skin.

01:44:51.800 --> 01:44:53.600
And what could they have done?

01:44:53.600 --> 01:44:54.680
Well, they could have died.

01:44:54.680 --> 01:44:58.240
They could have spread out and gotten away from each other.

01:44:58.240 --> 01:45:00.240
They could have formed a nice two-dimensional monolayer,

01:45:00.240 --> 01:45:01.680
the way that cell culture does.

01:45:01.680 --> 01:45:04.280
What they did instead was something quite different.

01:45:04.280 --> 01:45:05.800
Oops.

01:45:06.240 --> 01:45:09.200
What they did instead, after we put them

01:45:09.200 --> 01:45:11.680
in this little depression, all these little skin cells,

01:45:11.680 --> 01:45:16.120
they got together and they formed this round thing

01:45:16.120 --> 01:45:17.960
we call a xenobot.

01:45:17.960 --> 01:45:19.880
It's called a xenobot because Xenopus lavus

01:45:19.880 --> 01:45:20.720
is the name of the frog.

01:45:20.720 --> 01:45:23.520
And we think it's a biorebotics platform, so xenobot.

01:45:23.520 --> 01:45:25.680
What they do is these little guys

01:45:25.680 --> 01:45:30.200
achieve spontaneous motion by using their cilia.

01:45:30.200 --> 01:45:32.280
So frog skin has little hairs, little,

01:45:32.280 --> 01:45:33.720
motile hairs called cilia, which it

01:45:33.760 --> 01:45:36.600
uses to distribute mucus down the side of the animal.

01:45:36.600 --> 01:45:39.360
So instead, what they do is they use it to row against the water.

01:45:39.360 --> 01:45:40.520
So they start to swim.

01:45:40.520 --> 01:45:41.600
So they can go in circles.

01:45:41.600 --> 01:45:46.320
They can patrol back and forth like this.

01:45:46.320 --> 01:45:47.880
They can have these collective behaviors

01:45:47.880 --> 01:45:49.240
where they can go on a long journey

01:45:49.240 --> 01:45:50.760
or they can interact with each other

01:45:50.760 --> 01:45:53.960
or they can sit there doing nothing.

01:45:53.960 --> 01:45:55.880
They have all kinds of behaviors.

01:45:55.880 --> 01:46:00.080
Here's one moving in a maze in water.

01:46:00.080 --> 01:46:01.800
So you'll see what it does as it goes.

01:46:01.840 --> 01:46:04.080
It takes the corner without bumping into anything.

01:46:04.080 --> 01:46:06.680
And then at this point, it spontaneously decides to turn around

01:46:06.680 --> 01:46:07.960
and go back where it came from.

01:46:07.960 --> 01:46:09.000
We are not pacing it.

01:46:09.000 --> 01:46:10.200
We are not controlling it.

01:46:10.200 --> 01:46:12.280
There are no, there's no neurons here.

01:46:12.280 --> 01:46:17.160
This is a piece of skin living its own, its new best life.

01:46:17.160 --> 01:46:21.400
And you're watching some of its behaviors.

01:46:21.400 --> 01:46:26.560
It has all kinds of active calcium signaling.

01:46:26.560 --> 01:46:30.360
This is the same technology used to read out brain signaling.

01:46:30.440 --> 01:46:32.800
We are currently in the process of trying to decode all this

01:46:32.800 --> 01:46:34.720
to see what the cells are saying to each other.

01:46:34.720 --> 01:46:36.720
What are these two, what if anything

01:46:36.720 --> 01:46:38.920
are these two Xenobots saying to each other?

01:46:38.920 --> 01:46:40.120
They can regenerate.

01:46:40.120 --> 01:46:42.720
So if you cut them almost in half, they will seal up.

01:46:42.720 --> 01:46:43.560
So look at this.

01:46:43.560 --> 01:46:45.680
So here's like 180 degree hinge right there.

01:46:45.680 --> 01:46:48.720
Look at the power it takes to fold itself back

01:46:48.720 --> 01:46:51.040
into its new Xenobot shape.

01:46:51.040 --> 01:46:53.640
And something else that's amazing is by modeling.

01:46:53.640 --> 01:46:57.320
And so Josh Bongard and Sam Kriegman in his lab

01:46:57.320 --> 01:46:58.960
did a bunch of computational modeling

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:01.520
in the simulator of these bots running around.

01:47:01.520 --> 01:47:04.280
And they noticed a kind of unusual predicted behavior

01:47:04.280 --> 01:47:07.240
that they tend to rearrange their environment

01:47:07.240 --> 01:47:08.080
in this weird way.

01:47:08.080 --> 01:47:10.560
So they went, so we went ahead and we built some of the ones.

01:47:10.560 --> 01:47:13.400
Then again, Doug sculpted some of these things

01:47:13.400 --> 01:47:15.320
in ways that the AI suggested.

01:47:15.320 --> 01:47:17.800
And we discovered something remarkable,

01:47:17.800 --> 01:47:19.960
which is called kinematic replication.

01:47:21.360 --> 01:47:24.480
Notice that we've made it impossible for these animals

01:47:24.480 --> 01:47:26.760
to reproduce in the normal froggy fashion.

01:47:26.760 --> 01:47:27.920
They don't have any other things there.

01:47:27.920 --> 01:47:29.080
They're just skin.

01:47:29.080 --> 01:47:31.880
But within a couple of days,

01:47:31.880 --> 01:47:35.920
they discover a novel way of making copies of themselves

01:47:35.920 --> 01:47:37.560
that's basically Von Neumann's dream.

01:47:37.560 --> 01:47:40.480
It's able to construct copies of itself

01:47:40.480 --> 01:47:42.680
from material it finds in the environment.

01:47:42.680 --> 01:47:45.680
So this white stuff here, these are all loose skin cells

01:47:45.680 --> 01:47:47.800
that we sprinkled into their world.

01:47:47.800 --> 01:47:49.120
What they do is they run around

01:47:49.120 --> 01:47:52.240
and they both collectively and individually,

01:47:52.240 --> 01:47:54.480
they collect them into little balls

01:47:54.480 --> 01:47:56.440
and then they sort of polish these little balls

01:47:56.440 --> 01:47:57.800
and compact them.

01:47:57.800 --> 01:48:00.840
And because they're not working with a passive,

01:48:00.840 --> 01:48:02.560
some kind of passive particle,

01:48:02.560 --> 01:48:04.920
they're working with an agential material,

01:48:04.920 --> 01:48:07.160
just like we were the engineers,

01:48:07.160 --> 01:48:09.400
Doug Blackison was working with an agential material,

01:48:09.400 --> 01:48:10.880
these cells that have an agenda,

01:48:10.880 --> 01:48:13.160
they like to assemble into the xenobot.

01:48:13.160 --> 01:48:17.200
These little blobs become the next generation of xenobots.

01:48:17.200 --> 01:48:18.040
And guess what they do?

01:48:18.040 --> 01:48:19.360
They run around and collect more cells

01:48:19.360 --> 01:48:23.240
and they become the next generation of xenobots and so on.

01:48:23.240 --> 01:48:26.640
And so this ability to make copies of itself

01:48:26.640 --> 01:48:28.760
using kinematic replication is just one of them.

01:48:28.760 --> 01:48:31.480
We're just scratching the surface here of what they can do.

01:48:31.480 --> 01:48:34.040
There is much, much more coming.

01:48:34.040 --> 01:48:39.040
And so this suggests an interesting set of questions.

01:48:40.040 --> 01:48:45.040
What did the frog genome actually learn during evolution?

01:48:45.200 --> 01:48:46.680
Well, it can make frogs, sure,

01:48:46.680 --> 01:48:48.880
and this is the normal tadpole path,

01:48:48.880 --> 01:48:49.920
but it turns out,

01:48:49.920 --> 01:48:51.480
and something we would have never known

01:48:51.480 --> 01:48:53.840
if we hadn't tried this experiment,

01:48:53.840 --> 01:48:55.280
it actually can do other things.

01:48:55.280 --> 01:48:57.400
It can make the exact same genome.

01:48:57.400 --> 01:48:59.240
We didn't edit the genome here.

01:48:59.240 --> 01:49:01.480
We didn't give them any weird new nanomaterials.

01:49:02.560 --> 01:49:05.840
The same genome can have a different developmental path.

01:49:05.840 --> 01:49:07.880
This is what an old xenobot looks like.

01:49:07.880 --> 01:49:11.680
I mean, it has this weird structure

01:49:11.680 --> 01:49:13.400
that who knows what it's changing into.

01:49:13.400 --> 01:49:14.920
And then it has different behaviors

01:49:14.920 --> 01:49:17.600
that's different from what tadpoles do.

01:49:17.600 --> 01:49:19.360
So here's some interesting things about it.

01:49:19.360 --> 01:49:22.400
First of all, for any other creature,

01:49:22.400 --> 01:49:25.560
when you ask why does it look the way it looks?

01:49:25.560 --> 01:49:28.360
Why does it have certain behaviors and properties?

01:49:28.360 --> 01:49:30.160
The answer is always the same, well, evolution.

01:49:30.160 --> 01:49:31.240
So selection, right?

01:49:31.240 --> 01:49:36.240
So for eons, the system was shaped,

01:49:38.320 --> 01:49:40.360
it was selected for specific behaviors,

01:49:40.360 --> 01:49:42.320
everything else died out and there you go.

01:49:42.320 --> 01:49:45.000
But here, you can't use that story here

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:46.720
because there's never been any xenobots.

01:49:46.720 --> 01:49:49.280
There has never been any selection to be a good xenobot.

01:49:49.280 --> 01:49:53.040
Where did these capacities come from?

01:49:53.040 --> 01:49:56.760
Where did their ability to do kinematic self-replication,

01:49:56.760 --> 01:49:57.600
which to our knowledge,

01:49:57.600 --> 01:49:59.240
doesn't exist anywhere in the biosphere,

01:49:59.240 --> 01:50:00.640
where did that come from?

01:50:00.640 --> 01:50:04.040
Now, we don't know what their cognitive capacities are.

01:50:04.040 --> 01:50:05.040
We're studying that right now.

01:50:05.040 --> 01:50:05.880
What can they sense?

01:50:05.880 --> 01:50:06.720
Do they have preferences?

01:50:06.720 --> 01:50:07.920
How can they learn?

01:50:07.920 --> 01:50:10.280
We don't know any of that yet.

01:50:10.280 --> 01:50:12.200
But we do know that they have novel morphologies

01:50:12.200 --> 01:50:14.440
and novel behaviors and so where does that come from?

01:50:14.440 --> 01:50:16.920
So one way to think about this

01:50:16.920 --> 01:50:20.880
and that same genome by being probed in this way

01:50:20.880 --> 01:50:22.720
is showing us a bit of the latent space,

01:50:22.720 --> 01:50:24.320
a bit of what they are capable of.

01:50:24.320 --> 01:50:26.400
So this is kind of, you know, Jeremy Gay,

01:50:26.400 --> 01:50:27.840
who's an amazing graphic designer

01:50:27.840 --> 01:50:29.400
that does a lot of our artwork,

01:50:29.400 --> 01:50:32.880
did this homage to the famous Hofstadter book,

01:50:32.880 --> 01:50:33.920
Gerd Lescher Bach,

01:50:34.840 --> 01:50:39.840
where he was pointing out that how you look at certain objects

01:50:42.760 --> 01:50:44.800
reveals what you see and what they can do.

01:50:44.800 --> 01:50:46.640
And so through that frog genome,

01:50:46.680 --> 01:50:48.640
when you look through it in a particular way,

01:50:48.640 --> 01:50:50.840
yes, you can see the tadpoles

01:50:50.840 --> 01:50:52.000
and yes, you can see xenobots

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:53.880
and maybe you can see other things.

01:50:53.880 --> 01:50:56.160
And so what we can say here

01:50:56.160 --> 01:51:00.480
is that these kind of synthetic organisms

01:51:00.480 --> 01:51:01.880
are really a tool.

01:51:01.880 --> 01:51:04.120
They're almost like a periscope or a telescope

01:51:04.120 --> 01:51:06.880
that lets you look into another space

01:51:06.880 --> 01:51:09.760
that we normally don't see into the space of possibilities

01:51:09.760 --> 01:51:11.720
or for example, anatomical structure.

01:51:11.720 --> 01:51:12.920
And so for the last couple of minutes,

01:51:12.920 --> 01:51:14.040
I just wanna talk about this

01:51:14.040 --> 01:51:17.920
and the future of all this in bioengineering and so on.

01:51:17.920 --> 01:51:20.320
And the concepts that we wanna talk about are these.

01:51:20.320 --> 01:51:22.160
We've already talked about multiscale

01:51:22.160 --> 01:51:23.560
competency architecture.

01:51:23.560 --> 01:51:24.960
This idea of polycomputing,

01:51:24.960 --> 01:51:28.720
which Josh Bongard and I came up with to indicate

01:51:28.720 --> 01:51:30.760
the fact that any physical process

01:51:30.760 --> 01:51:32.560
can be treated as a computation,

01:51:32.560 --> 01:51:34.680
as a different computation by different observers,

01:51:34.680 --> 01:51:36.680
depending on how they interpret it.

01:51:36.680 --> 01:51:40.280
And that these observers ourselves observing each other

01:51:40.280 --> 01:51:43.480
and various conspecifics and parasites and so on,

01:51:44.560 --> 01:51:47.200
this idea that really because of this competency,

01:51:47.200 --> 01:51:50.400
because cells and tissues are not a passive material,

01:51:50.400 --> 01:51:54.360
every part is able to hack all the other parts

01:51:54.360 --> 01:51:57.480
by providing signals that exploit their functionality.

01:51:57.480 --> 01:51:59.000
Just like we as engineers,

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:00.840
and that whole middle part of the talk,

01:52:00.840 --> 01:52:02.360
I was trying to show you that

01:52:02.360 --> 01:52:06.240
triggering complex organ formation and so on,

01:52:06.240 --> 01:52:10.280
you don't have to try to micromanage the molecular steps.

01:52:10.280 --> 01:52:12.660
If you can communicate with a larger system

01:52:12.660 --> 01:52:14.060
to tell it what you want it to do,

01:52:14.060 --> 01:52:15.340
you can take advantage of that.

01:52:15.340 --> 01:52:18.860
Well, biology, we're late to that party as engineers,

01:52:18.860 --> 01:52:21.020
and biology has been doing this all along.

01:52:21.020 --> 01:52:23.260
So I wanna show you a couple of examples.

01:52:23.260 --> 01:52:25.740
The first thing I wanna just mention is,

01:52:25.740 --> 01:52:28.660
building with a gentile materials is very different.

01:52:28.660 --> 01:52:30.380
So when you build with a passive material,

01:52:30.380 --> 01:52:31.700
like making Legos,

01:52:31.700 --> 01:52:34.500
it's on you to put every Lego where it goes.

01:52:34.500 --> 01:52:35.980
All they do is hold shape.

01:52:35.980 --> 01:52:37.540
They have very little competencies

01:52:37.540 --> 01:52:38.660
besides holding their shape.

01:52:38.660 --> 01:52:39.940
So you have to control everything.

01:52:39.940 --> 01:52:41.540
This is molecular medicine.

01:52:41.540 --> 01:52:44.420
This is synthetic biology now.

01:52:44.420 --> 01:52:45.580
This is bioengineering.

01:52:45.580 --> 01:52:47.820
You build everything yourself.

01:52:47.820 --> 01:52:49.780
But so if you wanted to make a tower out of Legos,

01:52:49.780 --> 01:52:51.740
you have to put everything where it goes.

01:52:51.740 --> 01:52:52.580
It's easy.

01:52:52.580 --> 01:52:53.380
There are a few surprises,

01:52:53.380 --> 01:52:56.280
but the problem is if it falls down, that's it.

01:52:56.280 --> 01:52:59.340
You could try to make a tower out of dogs, for example.

01:52:59.340 --> 01:53:00.260
If you made a tower out of,

01:53:00.260 --> 01:53:01.500
if you tried it the old fashioned way

01:53:01.500 --> 01:53:04.220
by stacking dogs on top of each other, that doesn't work.

01:53:04.220 --> 01:53:05.820
The dogs have their own agendas.

01:53:05.820 --> 01:53:07.860
They're gonna walk off, not gonna work.

01:53:07.860 --> 01:53:09.740
But there's a new set of tools

01:53:10.740 --> 01:53:13.860
basically from different parts of this spectrum

01:53:13.860 --> 01:53:14.700
that we talked about,

01:53:14.700 --> 01:53:17.780
different ways of interacting with systems.

01:53:17.780 --> 01:53:20.140
If you don't insist on treating them as this kind of system,

01:53:20.140 --> 01:53:22.340
but you're open to the idea that your material

01:53:22.340 --> 01:53:24.380
might actually be this kind of system.

01:53:24.380 --> 01:53:26.020
And in the case of dogs, it's very obvious.

01:53:26.020 --> 01:53:28.380
In the case of cells, it's only now becoming apparent

01:53:28.380 --> 01:53:31.900
that they are also somewhere here.

01:53:31.900 --> 01:53:33.500
What you can do is train the dogs.

01:53:33.500 --> 01:53:34.820
It's a very different strategy.

01:53:34.820 --> 01:53:36.900
You're now doing behavior shaping

01:53:36.900 --> 01:53:38.600
as opposed to old school engineering.

01:53:38.600 --> 01:53:41.360
But the good news is that this tower repairs itself

01:53:41.360 --> 01:53:43.720
when you knock it down, they'll get right back up.

01:53:43.720 --> 01:53:46.200
And so the question about this competency is,

01:53:46.200 --> 01:53:48.280
what can you expect the subunits to do

01:53:48.280 --> 01:53:50.000
when you're not there to manage them?

01:53:50.000 --> 01:53:51.960
And how do you construct complex things

01:53:51.960 --> 01:53:53.600
out of units like that?

01:53:53.600 --> 01:53:57.000
And the way you do it is by using their natural interface,

01:53:57.000 --> 01:53:59.280
in this case, learning rewards and punishments

01:53:59.280 --> 01:54:00.800
to control their behavior.

01:54:00.800 --> 01:54:01.880
This is hacking.

01:54:01.880 --> 01:54:04.360
Hacking not in the sense of the people

01:54:04.360 --> 01:54:05.640
who steal your credit card numbers,

01:54:05.640 --> 01:54:08.000
but in the sense of using a system

01:54:08.000 --> 01:54:11.720
in not necessarily the way that it was intended to be used,

01:54:11.720 --> 01:54:13.640
but in some clever way that exploits

01:54:13.640 --> 01:54:17.960
the system's own properties for a complex outcome.

01:54:17.960 --> 01:54:20.120
So we see this all the time in behavioral science, right?

01:54:20.120 --> 01:54:22.080
So there are these crazy parasites,

01:54:22.080 --> 01:54:26.040
this toxoplasma that causes animals and humans

01:54:26.040 --> 01:54:27.960
to become less risk averse.

01:54:27.960 --> 01:54:29.400
So captains of industry and people

01:54:29.400 --> 01:54:31.760
who die on motorcycle accidents going too fast

01:54:31.760 --> 01:54:33.520
tend to be infected with this stuff

01:54:33.560 --> 01:54:38.560
because it actually changes your risk aversion level.

01:54:38.720 --> 01:54:42.640
And we've got a fungus that controls ant behavior

01:54:42.640 --> 01:54:43.480
and so on.

01:54:43.480 --> 01:54:47.000
So we know that creatures hack each other's behavioral policies

01:54:47.000 --> 01:54:49.440
for navigating three-dimensional space,

01:54:49.440 --> 01:54:50.280
but that's not all.

01:54:50.280 --> 01:54:52.600
What we're now starting to understand

01:54:52.600 --> 01:54:55.760
is that they're really interesting hacks

01:54:55.760 --> 01:54:59.080
that happen in anatomical and physiological spaces.

01:54:59.080 --> 01:55:02.160
In order to do that, the material, right?

01:55:02.160 --> 01:55:03.280
It's a gentle matter.

01:55:03.280 --> 01:55:06.520
The material on which evolution works,

01:55:06.520 --> 01:55:10.240
so cells and tissues, has to have these various competencies.

01:55:10.240 --> 01:55:11.160
It has to have memories.

01:55:11.160 --> 01:55:13.640
It has to be able to measure things to take in inputs.

01:55:13.640 --> 01:55:16.920
You can't hack something that doesn't have any of that,

01:55:16.920 --> 01:55:17.920
but life does.

01:55:17.920 --> 01:55:19.280
And I wanna show you a couple of examples

01:55:19.280 --> 01:55:21.240
of this plasticity.

01:55:21.240 --> 01:55:24.000
So here is, and this is not Photoshop,

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:27.160
this is, these are real animals.

01:55:27.160 --> 01:55:30.400
These are flies and on their wings,

01:55:30.400 --> 01:55:32.720
they are running a kind of stripped down

01:55:32.720 --> 01:55:34.320
ant morphogenetic program,

01:55:34.320 --> 01:55:36.640
like a two-dimensional ant morphogenetic program.

01:55:36.640 --> 01:55:38.680
And the reason they do it is because when they flap their

01:55:38.680 --> 01:55:40.000
wings in a particular pattern,

01:55:40.000 --> 01:55:41.360
it looks like ants scurrying around

01:55:41.360 --> 01:55:43.280
and their predators don't wanna deal with the ants

01:55:43.280 --> 01:55:45.040
and they scare them off.

01:55:45.040 --> 01:55:48.120
So it's kind of amazing that on their wings,

01:55:48.120 --> 01:55:51.640
they're able to have these very specific patterns,

01:55:51.640 --> 01:55:53.400
but it's no more amazing than the fly itself.

01:55:53.400 --> 01:55:56.000
I mean, this is just a simplified version

01:55:56.000 --> 01:55:57.720
of what the fly itself is doing,

01:55:57.720 --> 01:55:59.000
but it's in computer sciences,

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:00.280
would be kind of virtualization.

01:56:00.280 --> 01:56:02.680
The fact that the same tissue can actually make

01:56:02.680 --> 01:56:05.000
different kinds of patterns.

01:56:05.000 --> 01:56:07.080
Now, I wanna show you one of my favorite examples

01:56:07.080 --> 01:56:09.400
of that kind of hacking.

01:56:09.400 --> 01:56:11.240
